author: Blackbird
text:
Checkpoint: I was on an expedition to map the jungle for reconnaissance purposes, looking down from my cockpit window, I saw various outposts deep in the jungle canopy that made me wonder who else had been here? Foreign entities setting up? This deep in the jungle? Surely I was the first. Little was I aware that the fuel lines on my single-seater craft hadn't been properly secured, I began rapidly losing altitude before getting suspended from a few trees 20 ft above the jungle floor. "Not to worry" I gaffed before realizing this was an unfamiliar land & I was in way over my head. 
Before exiting the craft, I made sure to leave its floodlight and emergency radar on just in case.
 
I set up camp not far away from the crash, using the spotlight to keep my lit in the dark. On night one I heard howling and snarling from somewhere nearby, and swore I saw someone watching me.. Eerie, I kept my arsenal close.. my Colt and machete ready. On morning of day two I realized somebody had been through my camp, something with massive lizard-like feet. This left me feeling rather terrified. My leftover rations had been ransacked; there was nothing left to survive on here. I had to start making moves..
 So I packed my leftover belongings, and began slashing my way through thorn, thimble and vine with my trusty machete. Good thing I was watching my step, the shallow water I crossed was full of these strange, small, blue gators?? Regardless, keeping my whit, I traveled forward. 

 On the evening of day two, as I reached a high point just above the jungle canopy, I saw light billowing from a cave just Northeast of my position. In a haste, I marked my position using a stick, cloth from my vest, and a little leftover amount of fuel from the plane crash to create a couple makeshift torches, one for me, one to mark the hill. Keeping my bearing and using what little landmarks available, I made it to the mouth of the cave. Peering inside I saw a family of large apes, with what looked to be a massive pile of Bananas. My foot slipped on some loose pebbles causing them to turn around, I turned ghost grey. The biggest monky let out an "OOO", it frightened me at first, until I realized he wasn't approaching me in anger, rather out of curiosity. As he got closer I winced and nearly lost balance, before he opened his giant palm to lend me a hand. The large ape smiled, and offered me a Banana. I accepted, and stuck around for a little, reacquiring my focus, trying to wrap my head around why these apes were so nice. Time began to fly, the apes of the cave were quite the artists, even though they didn't speak a language I could understand; their drawings taught me a lot about the jungle & themselves. They played beautiful music on makeshift instruments (if you can call them that) that brought nostalgia of times I had never lived.. 

Truly making the best out of anything and everything they had. Doing my best to gesture that I had to go soon, one pointed towards the backside of the cave. A small opening was visible, with a tremendous view on the other side.

Knowing I couldn't stay here forever, and furthermore remembering how I got here, I gave the apes of the cave each a keepsake from my bag, and headed on my way out the small exit. Good thing I held on to those tools from the plane. Maybe they'll get inventive after I'm gone. 

When I peered out of the exit, the sun was just about to come up. "Had it really been a whole night in that cave?" It was like I skipped forward in time. Ahead of me, a great canyon with a small river flowing through it appeared through the last few trees. 

The timing of what happened next, was like a movie; as I exited the edge of the greenery, and began descending the cliff side, I saw a plane flying rather low nearby, now is my chance, and that looks like one of our planes! I quickly pulled my SOS mirror from my cargo pants pocket and began reflecting it against the plane, he spotted me quickly, making a sharp turn and bringing it in right next to the river! 

As I climbed aboard the Beechcraft, and looked toward the cave where I made those unlikely friends, I saw them waving at me. For a moment, I wondered; was I supposed to stay here? Or perhaps, a more significant checkpoint awaits me somewhere not so far away... "Well aren't you certainly lucky they sent me, sir. I don't think many could land in such a rough and uneven spot with a twin engine." the pilot chortled. The plane began accelerating, while the weightlessness of liftoff took over, I wondered if I'd ever revisit the jungle, even if it was just another near tragic mistake. Alas, I write this from the plane window, on my way back to base. But still I wonder, what were those other outposts so deep in the jungle? Others like me maybe who weren't so lucky? Guess I may never know.. for now.. but I'll be back, journal and gear in hand. Until next time, Bon-Voyage adventurers.

Billions of years passed before we were born, who knows how many will pass after. We are here right here and now, we cannot comprehend anything beyond that without spiraling into existential dread. But it's okay. It's okay to fear the end. But if you are reading this do not be afraid, because you are alive right now. Everytime you feel that fear clutch your heart as the inevitability of death strikes you, remember that means you are alive. You cannot fear death once it has you, just as you cannot comprehend life before you have it. It will be okay, you are alive now, that is all that matters. All I can say is tell those you love every day what they mean to you. Our time is short and limited but it is not meaningless. You mean something, you exist. Even in a trillion years when all human life is gone you will still have existed. That is the only certainty we have, cherish it, do not throw that away, you are worth so so much more than you know.
